# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ramsey-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] In mathematics, the **Hales–Jewett theorem** is a fundamental combinatorial result of Ramsey theory, named after Alfred W.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] Jewett, that concerns the degree to which high-dimensional objects must necessarily exhibit some combinatorial structure.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] By a standard strategy-stealing argument, one can thus conclude that if two players alternate, then the first player has a winning strategy when *H* is sufficiently large, though no practical algorithm for obtaining this strategy is known.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] Let *W**H* *n* be the set of words of length *H* over an alphabet with *n* letters; that is, the set of sequences of {1, 2, ..., *n*} of length *H*.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] This set forms the hypercube that is the subject of the theorem.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] A *variable word* *w*(*x*) over *W**H* *n* still has length *H* but includes the special element *x* in place of at least one of the letters.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] The words *w*(1), *w*(2), ..., *w*(*n*) obtained by replacing all instances of the special element *x* with 1, 2, ..., *n*, form a combinatorial line in the space *W**H* *n*; combinatorial lines correspond to rows, columns, and (some of the) diagonals of the hypercube.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] The Hales–Jewett theorem then states that for given positive integers *n* and *c*, there exists a positive integer *H*, depending on *n* and *c*, such that for any partition of *W**H* *n* into *c* parts, there is at least one part that contains an entire combinatorial line.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] A typical combinatorial line would be the word 2x, which corresponds to the line 21, 22, 23; another combinatorial line is xx, which is the line 11, 22, 33.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] We now prove the Hales–Jewett theorem in the special case *n* = 3, *c* = 2, *H* = 8 discussed above.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] The idea is to reduce this task to that of proving simpler versions of the Hales–Jewett theorem (in this particular case, to the cases *n* = 2, *c* = 2, *H* = 2 and *n* = 2, *c* = 6, *H* = 6).
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] One can prove the general case of the Hales–Jewett theorem by similar methods, using mathematical induction.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] Each element of the hypercube *W*8 3 is a string of eight numbers from 1 to 3, e.g.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] 13211321 is an element of the hypercube.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] We are assuming that this hypercube is completely filled with "noughts" and "crosses".
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] We shall use a proof by contradiction and assume that neither the set of noughts nor the set of crosses contains a combinatorial line.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] If we fix the first six elements of such a string and let the last two vary, we obtain an ordinary tic-tac-toe board, for instance "132113??" gives such a board.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] For each such board "abcdef??", we consider the positions "abcdef11", "abcdef12", "abcdef22".
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] Each of these must be filled with either a nought or a cross, so by the pigeonhole principle two of them must be filled with the same symbol.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] Since any two of these positions are part of a combinatorial line, the third element of that line must be occupied by the opposite symbol (since we are assuming that no combinatorial line has all three elements filled with the same symbol).
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] 2. abcdef11 and abcdef22 are noughts; abcdef33 is a cross.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] 3. abcdef12 and abcdef22 are noughts; abcdef32 is a cross.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] 4. abcdef11 and abcdef12 are crosses; abcdef13 is a nought.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] 5. abcdef11 and abcdef22 are crosses; abcdef33 is a nought.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] 6. abcdef12 and abcdef22 are crosses; abcdef32 is a nought.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] Thus we can partition the six-dimensional hypercube *W*6 3 into six classes, corresponding to each of the above six possibilities.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] (If an element abcdef obeys multiple possibilities, we can choose one arbitrarily, e.g. by choosing the highest one on the above list).
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] By the pigeonhole principle, two of these elements must fall into the same class.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] But now consider the position 11333233, which must be filled with either a cross or a nought.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] If it is filled with a cross, then the combinatorial line 11xxx2xx is filled entirely with crosses, contradicting our hypothesis.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] If instead it is filled with a nought, then the combinatorial line 11xxx233 is filled entirely with noughts, again contradicting our hypothesis.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] Similarly if any other two of the above seven elements of *W*6 3 fall into the same class.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] Since we have a contradiction in all cases, the original hypothesis must be false; thus there must exist at least one combinatorial line consisting entirely of noughts or entirely of crosses.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] The above argument was somewhat wasteful; in fact the same theorem holds for *H* = 4.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] If one extends the above argument to general values of *n* and *c*, then *H* will grow very fast; even when *c* = 2 (which corresponds to two-player tic-tac-toe) the *H* given by the above argument grows as fast as the Ackermann function.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] The first primitive recursive bound is due to Saharon Shelah, and is still the best known bound in general for the *Hales–Jewett number* *H* = *H*(*n*, *c*).
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] This is simply because all of the combinatorial lines appearing in the above proof of the Hales–Jewett theorem, also form arithmetic progressions in decimal notation.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] A more general formulation of this argument can be used to show that the Hales–Jewett theorem generalizes van der Waerden's theorem.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] Indeed the Hales–Jewett theorem is substantially a stronger theorem.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] Just as van der Waerden's theorem has a stronger *density version* in Szemerédi's theorem, the Hales–Jewett theorem also has a density version.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] In this strengthened version of the Hales–Jewett theorem, instead of coloring the entire hypercube *W**H* *n* into *c* colors, one is given an arbitrary subset *A* of the hypercube *W**H* *n* with some given density 0 < δ < 1.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] The theorem states that if *H* is sufficiently large depending on *n* and δ, then the set *A* must necessarily contain an entire combinatorial line.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] The density Hales–Jewett theorem was originally proved by Furstenberg and Katznelson using ergodic theory.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] In 2009, the Polymath Project developed a new proof of the density Hales–Jewett theorem based on ideas from the proof of the corners theorem.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] Dodos, Kanellopoulos, and Tyros gave a simplified version of the Polymath proof.
[src:ramsey-theory/hales-jewett-theorem] The Hales–Jewett theorem is further generalized by the Graham–Rothschild theorem on higher-dimensional combinatorial cubes.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] In combinatorics, **Ramsey's theorem**, in one of its graph-theoretic forms, states that one will find monochromatic cliques in any edge labelling (with colours) of a sufficiently large complete graph.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] As the simplest example, consider two colours (say, blue and red).
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Let r and s be any two positive integers.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Ramsey's theorem states that there exists a least positive integer *R*(*r*, *s*) for which every blue-red edge colouring of the complete graph on *R*(*r*, *s*) vertices contains a blue clique on r vertices or a red clique on s vertices.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Ramsey's theorem is a foundational result in combinatorics.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The first version of this result was proved by Frank Ramsey.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] This initiated the combinatorial theory now called Ramsey theory, that seeks regularity amid disorder: general conditions for the existence of substructures with regular properties.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] In this application it is a question of the existence of *monochromatic subsets*, that is, subsets of connected edges of just one colour.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] An extension of this theorem applies to any finite number of colours, rather than just two.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Suppose the edges of a complete graph on 6 vertices are coloured red and blue.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] There are 5 edges incident to v and so (by the pigeonhole principle) at least 3 of them must be the same colour.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Without loss of generality we can assume at least 3 of these edges, connecting the vertex, v, to vertices, r, s and t, are blue.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] (If not, exchange red and blue in what follows.) If any of the edges, (*rs*), (*rt*), (*st*), are also blue then we have an entirely blue triangle.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] If not, then those three edges are all red and we have an entirely red triangle.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Since this argument works for any colouring, *any* *K*6 contains a monochromatic *K*3, and therefore *R*(3, 3) ≤ 6.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The popular version of this is called the theorem on friends and strangers.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] An alternative proof works by double counting.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] It goes as follows: Count the number of ordered triples of vertices, x, y, z, such that the edge, (*xy*), is red and the edge, (*yz*), is blue.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Firstly, any given vertex will be the middle of either 0 × 5 = 0 (all edges from the vertex are the same colour), 1 × 4 = 4 (four are the same colour, one is the other colour), or 2 × 3 = 6 (three are the same colour, two are the other colour) such triples.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Therefore, there are at most 6 × 6 = 36 such triples.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Secondly, for any non-monochromatic triangle (*xyz*), there exist precisely two such triples.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Therefore, there are at most 18 non-monochromatic triangles.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Therefore, at least 2 of the 20 triangles in the *K*6 are monochromatic.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Conversely, it is possible to 2-colour a *K*5 without creating any monochromatic *K*3, showing that *R*(3, 3) > 5.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The unique colouring is shown to the right.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The task of proving that *R*(3, 3) ≤ 6 was one of the problems of William Lowell Putnam Mathematical Competition in 1953, as well as in the Hungarian Math Olympiad in 1947.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] , up to isomorphism and permutation of colors: the untwisted (left) and twisted (right) colorings.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] A multicolour Ramsey number is a Ramsey number using 3 or more colours.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] There are (up to symmetries) only two non-trivial multicolour Ramsey numbers for which the exact value is known, namely *R*(3, 3, 3) = 17 and *R*(3, 3, 4) = 30.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Suppose that we have an edge colouring of a complete graph using 3 colours, red, green and blue.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Suppose further that the edge colouring has no monochromatic triangles.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Consider the set of vertices that have a red edge to the vertex v.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] This is called the red neighbourhood of v.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The red neighbourhood of v cannot contain any red edges, since otherwise there would be a red triangle consisting of the two endpoints of that red edge and the vertex v.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Thus, the induced edge colouring on the red neighbourhood of v has edges coloured with only two colours, namely green and blue.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Since *R*(3, 3) = 6, the red neighbourhood of v can contain at most 5 vertices.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Similarly, the green and blue neighbourhoods of v can contain at most 5 vertices each.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Since every vertex, except for v itself, is in one of the red, green or blue neighbourhoods of v, the entire complete graph can have at most 1 + 5 + 5 + 5 = 16 vertices.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] To see that *R*(3, 3, 3) = 17, it suffices to draw an edge colouring on the complete graph on 16 vertices with 3 colours that avoids monochromatic triangles.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] It turns out that there are exactly two such colourings on *K*16, the so-called untwisted and twisted colourings.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Both colourings are shown in the figures to the right, with the untwisted colouring on the left, and the twisted colouring on the right.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] If we select any colour of either the untwisted or twisted colouring on *K*16, and consider the graph whose edges are precisely those edges that have the specified colour, we will get the Clebsch graph.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] It is known that there are exactly two edge colourings with 3 colours on *K*15 that avoid monochromatic triangles, which can be constructed by deleting any vertex from the untwisted and twisted colourings on *K*16, respectively.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] It is also known that there are exactly 115 edge colourings with 3 colours on *K*14 that avoid monochromatic triangles, provided that we consider edge colourings that differ by a permutation of the colours as being the same.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] It is of interest to find the sequence of the multicolor Ramsey numbers R(3,3,...,3), where there are n 3's.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The sequence currently is only known up to *n* = 3, with the bounds for values as early as *n* = 4 being relatively loose: 51 ≤ *a*(4) ≤ 62.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The theorem for the 2-colour case can be proved by induction on *r* + *s*.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] It is clear from the definition that for all n, *R*(*n*, 2) = *R*(2, *n*) = *n*.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] We prove that *R*(*r*, *s*) exists by finding an explicit bound for it.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Lemma 1 implies that any *R*(*r*,*s*) is finite.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The right hand side of the inequality in Lemma 2 expresses a Ramsey number for c colours in terms of Ramsey numbers for fewer colours.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Therefore, any *R*(*n*1, …, *nc*) is finite for any number of colours.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The numbers *R*(*r*, *s*) in Ramsey's theorem (and their extensions to more than two colours) are known as Ramsey numbers.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The Ramsey number *R*(*m*, *n*) gives the solution to the party problem, which asks the minimum number of guests, *R*(*m*, *n*), that must be invited so that at least m will know each other or at least n will not know each other.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] In the language of graph theory, the Ramsey number is the minimum number of vertices, *v* = *R*(*m*, *n*), such that all undirected simple graphs of order v, contain a clique of order m, or an independent set of order n.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Ramsey's theorem states that such a number exists for all m and n.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] An upper bound for *R*(*r*, *s*) can be extracted from the proof of the theorem, and other arguments give lower bounds.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] (The first exponential lower bound was obtained by Paul Erdős using the probabilistic method.) However, there is a vast gap between the tightest lower bounds and the tightest upper bounds.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] There are also very few numbers r and s for which we know the exact value of *R*(*r*, *s*).
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Computing a lower bound L for *R*(*r*, *s*) usually requires exhibiting a blue/red colouring of the graph *K**L*−1 with no blue Kr subgraph and no red Ks subgraph.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Such a counterexample is called a *Ramsey graph*.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Brendan McKay maintains a list of known Ramsey graphs.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Upper bounds are often considerably more difficult to establish: one either has to check all possible colourings to confirm the absence of a counterexample, or to present a mathematical argument for its absence.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] A sophisticated computer program does not need to look at all colourings individually in order to eliminate all of them; nevertheless it is a very difficult computational task that existing software can only manage on small sizes.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Each complete graph Kn has ⁠1/2⁠*n*(*n* − 1) edges, so there would be a total of *c**n*(*n* − 1)/2 graphs to search through (for *c* colours) if brute force is used.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Therefore, the complexity for searching all possible graphs (via brute force) is *O*(*c**n*2) for c colourings and at most n nodes.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The situation is unlikely to improve with the advent of quantum computers.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] One of the best-known searching algorithms for unstructured datasets exhibits only a quadratic speedup (cf.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Grover's algorithm) relative to classical computers, so that the computation time is still exponential in the number of nodes.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] There are only two (4, 4, 16) graphs (that is, 2-colourings of a complete graph on 16 nodes without 4-node red or blue complete subgraphs) among 6.4 × 1022 different 2-colourings of 16-node graphs, and only one (4, 4, 17) graph (the Paley graph of order 17) among 2.46 × 1026 colourings.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The fact that *R*(4, 5) = 25 was first established by Brendan McKay and Stanisław Radziszowski in 1995.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The exact value of *R*(5, 5) is unknown, although it is known to lie between 43 (Geoffrey Exoo (1989)) and 46 (Angeltveit and McKay (2024)), inclusive.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] In 1997, McKay, Radziszowski and Exoo employed computer-assisted graph generation methods to conjecture that *R*(5, 5) = 43.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] They were able to construct exactly 656 (5, 5, 42) graphs, arriving at the same set of graphs through different routes.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] None of the 656 graphs can be extended to a (5, 5, 43) graph.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] In 2025, Tamburini performed a heuristic numerical calculation which identified 45 as "the most promising candidate" for *R*(5, 5).
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] For *R*(*r*, *s*) with *r*, *s* > 5, only weak bounds are available.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Lower bounds for *R*(6, 6) and *R*(8, 8) have not been improved since 1965 and 1972, respectively.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The standard survey on the development of Ramsey number research is the *Dynamic Survey 1* of the *Electronic Journal of Combinatorics*, by Radziszowski, which is periodically updated.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Where not cited otherwise, entries in the table below are taken from the June 2024 edition.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] It is also interesting that Erdős showed R(*P*n, *K*m) = (n − 1).(m − 1) + 1, for a path and a complete graph with n and m vertices respectively.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Also Chvatal showed R(*T*n, *K*m) = (n − 1).(m − 1) + 1, for a tree and a complete graph with n and m vertices respectively.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] These two theorems are the best examples of formulating Ramsey numbers for some special graphs.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] was given by Erdős in 1947 and was instrumental in his introduction of the probabilistic method.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] There is a huge gap between these two bounds: for example, for *s* = 10, this gives 101 ≤ *R*(10, 10) ≤ 48,620.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Nevertheless, the exponential growth factors of either bound were not improved for a long time, and for the lower bound it still stands at √2.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] There is no known explicit construction producing an exponential lower bound.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The upper bound for *R*(3, *t*) is given by Ajtai, Komlós, and Szemerédi, the lower bound was obtained originally by Kim, and the implicit constant was improved independently by Fiz Pontiveros, Griffiths and Morris, and Bohman and Keevash, by analysing the triangle-free process.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Mattheus and Verstraete (2024) gave a lower bound of $R(4,t)\geq c'_{s}t^{3}(\log t)^{-4}$ , determining the asymptotics of $R(4,t)$ up to logarithmic factors, and settling a question of Erdős, who offered 250 dollars for a proof that the lower limit has form $c'_{s}t^{3}(\log t)^{-d}$ .
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The Ramsey number $R(3,8)$ and $R(3,9)$ have been formally verified to be 28 and 36.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] This verification was achieved using a combination of Boolean satisfiability (SAT) solving and computer algebra systems (CAS).
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The proof was generated automatically using the SAT+CAS approach, marking the first certifiable proof of $R(3,8)=28$ and $R(3,9)=36$ .
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The verification process for $R(3,8)$ and $R(3,9)$ was conducted using the SAT+CAS framework MathCheck, which integrates a SAT solver with a computer algebra system.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The verification for $R(3,8)=28$ was completed in approximately 8 hours of wall clock time, producing a total proof size of 5.8 GiB.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The verification for $R(3,9)=36$ was significantly more computationally intensive, requiring 26 hours of wall clock time and generating 289 GiB of proof data.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The correctness of these results was independently verified using a modified version of the DRAT-trim proof checker.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The Ramsey number $R(4,5)$ has been formally verified to be 25.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The original proof, developed by McKay and Radziszowski in 1995, combined high-level mathematical arguments with computational steps and used multiple independent implementations to reduce the possibility of programming errors.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The formal proof was carried out using the HOL4 interactive theorem prover, limiting the potential for errors to the HOL4 kernel.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Rather than directly verifying the original algorithms, the authors utilized HOL4's interface to the MiniSat SAT solver to formally prove key gluing lemmas.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] There is a less well-known yet interesting analogue of Ramsey's theorem for induced subgraphs.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Roughly speaking, instead of finding a monochromatic subgraph, we are now required to find a monochromatic induced subgraph.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] In this variant, it is no longer sufficient to restrict our focus to complete graphs, since the existence of a complete subgraph does not imply the existence of an induced subgraph.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The qualitative statement of the theorem in the next section was first proven independently by Erdős, Hajnal and Pósa, Deuber and Rödl in the 1970s.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Since then, there has been much research in obtaining good bounds for induced Ramsey numbers.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Then, there exists a graph G such that any coloring of the edges of G using two colors contains a monochromatic induced copy of H (i.e. an induced subgraph of G such that it is isomorphic to H and its edges are monochromatic).
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The smallest possible number of vertices of G is the **induced Ramsey number** *r*ind(*H*).
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Sometimes, we also consider the asymmetric version of the problem.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] We define *r*ind(*X*,*Y*) to be the smallest possible number of vertices of a graph G such that every coloring of the edges of G using only red or blue contains a red induced subgraph of X or blue induced subgraph of Y.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Similar to Ramsey's theorem, it is unclear a priori whether induced Ramsey numbers exist for every graph H.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] In the early 1970s, Erdős, Hajnal and Pósa, Deuber, and Rödl independently proved that this is the case.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] However, the original proofs gave terrible bounds (e.g. towers of twos) on the induced Ramsey numbers.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] It is interesting to ask if better bounds can be achieved.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] In 1974, Paul Erdős conjectured that there exists a constant c such that every graph H on k vertices satisfies *r*ind(*H*) ≤ 2*ck*.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] If this conjecture is true, it would be optimal up to the constant c because the complete graph achieves a lower bound of this form (in fact, it's the same as Ramsey numbers).
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] However, this conjecture is still open as of now.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] However, that was still far from the exponential bound conjectured by Erdős.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] It was not until 1998 when a major breakthrough was achieved by Kohayakawa, Prömel and Rödl, who proved the first almost-exponential bound of *r*ind(*H*) ≤ 2*ck*(log *k*)2 for some constant c.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Their approach was to consider a suitable random graph constructed on projective planes and show that it has the desired properties with nonzero probability.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The idea of using random graphs on projective planes have also previously been used in studying Ramsey properties with respect to vertex colorings and the induced Ramsey problem on bounded degree graphs H.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Kohayakawa, Prömel and Rödl's bound remained the best general bound for a decade.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] In 2008, Fox and Sudakov provided an explicit construction for induced Ramsey numbers with the same bound.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] In fact, they showed that every (*n*,*d*,λ)-graph G with small λ and suitable d contains an induced monochromatic copy of any graph on k vertices in any coloring of edges of G in two colors.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] In particular, for some constant c, the Paley graph on *n* ≥ 2*ck* log2*k* vertices is such that all of its edge colorings in two colors contain an induced monochromatic copy of every k-vertex graph.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] In 2010, Conlon, Fox and Sudakov were able to improve the bound to *r*ind(*H*) ≤ 2*ck* log *k*, which remains the current best upper bound for general induced Ramsey numbers.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Similar to the previous work in 2008, they showed that every (*n*,*d*,λ)-graph G with small λ and edge density 1⁄2 contains an induced monochromatic copy of every graph on k vertices in any edge coloring in two colors.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Currently, Erdős's conjecture that *r*ind(*H*) ≤ 2*ck* remains open and is one of the important problems in extremal graph theory.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] For lower bounds, not much is known in general except for the fact that induced Ramsey numbers must be at least the corresponding Ramsey numbers.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Some lower bounds have been obtained for some special cases (see Special Cases).
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] It is sometimes quite difficult to compute the Ramsey number.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] While the general bounds for the induced Ramsey numbers are exponential in the size of the graph, the behaviour is much different on special classes of graphs (in particular, sparse ones).
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Many of these classes have induced Ramsey numbers polynomial in the number of vertices.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] If H is a cycle, path or star on k vertices, it is known that *r*ind(*H*) is linear in k.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] If H is a tree on k vertices, it is known that *r*ind(*H*) = *O*(*k*2 log2*k*).
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] It is also known that *r*ind(*H*) is superlinear (i.e.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Note that this is in contrast to the usual Ramsey numbers, where the Burr–Erdős conjecture (now proven) tells us that *r*(*H*) is linear (since trees are 1-degenerate).
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] For graphs H with number of vertices k and bounded degree Δ, it was conjectured that *r*ind(*H*) ≤ *cn**d*(Δ), for some constant d depending only on Δ.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] This result was first proven by Łuczak and Rödl in 1996, with *d*(Δ) growing as a tower of twos with height *O*(Δ2).
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] More reasonable bounds for *d*(Δ) were obtained since then.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] In 2013, Conlon, Fox and Zhao showed using a counting lemma for sparse pseudorandom graphs that *r*ind(*H*) ≤ *cn*2Δ+8, where the exponent is best possible up to constant factors.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Similar to Ramsey numbers, we can generalize the notion of induced Ramsey numbers to hypergraphs and multicolor settings.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] We can also generalize the induced Ramsey's theorem to a multicolor setting.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] It is possible to derive a bound on *r*ind(*H*;*q*) which is approximately a tower of two of height ~ log *q* by iteratively applying the bound on the two-color case.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The current best known bound is due to Fox and Sudakov, which achieves *r*ind(*H*;*q*) ≤ 2*ck*3, where k is the number of vertices of H and c is a constant depending only on q.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] We can extend the definition of induced Ramsey numbers to d-uniform hypergraphs by simply changing the word *graph* in the statement to *hypergraph*.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Furthermore, we can define the multicolor version of induced Ramsey numbers in the same way as the previous subsection.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Let H be a d-uniform hypergraph with k vertices.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Using the hypergraph container method, Conlon, Dellamonica, La Fleur, Rödl and Schacht were able to show that for *d* ≥ 3, *q* ≥ 2, *r*ind(*H*;*q*) ≤ *td*(*ck*) for some constant c depending on only d and q.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] In particular, this result mirrors the best known bound for the usual Ramsey number when *d* = 3.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] A further result, also commonly called *Ramsey's theorem*, applies to infinite graphs.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] In a context where finite graphs are also being discussed it is often called the "Infinite Ramsey theorem".
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] As intuition provided by the pictorial representation of a graph is diminished when moving from finite to infinite graphs, theorems in this area are usually phrased in set-theoretic terminology.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] A stronger but unbalanced infinite form of Ramsey's theorem for graphs, the Erdős–Dushnik–Miller theorem, states that every infinite graph contains either a countably infinite independent set, or an infinite clique of the same cardinality as the original graph.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] It is possible to deduce the finite Ramsey theorem from the infinite version by a proof by contradiction.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Suppose the finite Ramsey theorem is false.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Then there exist integers c, n, T such that for every integer k, there exists a c-colouring of [*k*](*n*) without a monochromatic set of size T.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Let Ck denote the c-colourings of [*k*](*n*) without a monochromatic set of size T.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] For any k, the restriction of a colouring in *C**k*+1 to [*k*](*n*) (by ignoring the colour of all sets containing *k* + 1) is a colouring in Ck.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Define ⁠ $C_{k}^{1}$ ⁠ to be the colourings in Ck which are restrictions of colourings in *C**k*+1.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Similarly, the restriction of any colouring in ⁠ $C_{k+1}^{1}$ ⁠ is in ⁠ $C_{k}^{1}$ ⁠, allowing one to define ⁠ $C_{k}^{2}$ ⁠ as the set of all such restrictions, a non-empty set.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Continuing so, define ⁠ $C_{k}^{m}$ ⁠ for all integers m, k.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Then every colouring in Dk is the restriction of a colouring in *D**k*+1.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Therefore, by unrestricting a colouring in Dk to a colouring in *D**k*+1, and continuing doing so, one constructs a colouring of $\mathbb {N} ^{(n)}$ without any monochromatic set of size T.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] This contradicts the infinite Ramsey theorem.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] If a suitable topological viewpoint is taken, this argument becomes a standard compactness argument showing that the infinite version of the theorem implies the finite version.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The theorem can also be extended to hypergraphs.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] An m-hypergraph is a graph whose "edges" are sets of m vertices – in a normal graph an edge is a set of 2 vertices.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] This theorem is usually proved by induction on m, the 'hyper-ness' of the graph.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The base case for the proof is *m* = 2, which is exactly the theorem above.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] For *m* = 3 we know the exact value of one non-trivial Ramsey number, namely *R*(4, 4; 3) = 13.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] This fact was established by Brendan McKay and Stanisław Radziszowski in 1991.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] It is also possible to define Ramsey numbers for *directed* graphs; these were introduced by P.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Let *R*(*n*) be the smallest number Q such that any complete graph with singly directed arcs (also called a "tournament") and with ≥ *Q* nodes contains an acyclic (also called "transitive") n-node subtournament.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] This is the directed-graph analogue of what (above) has been called *R*(*n*, *n*; 2), the smallest number Z such that any 2-colouring of the edges of a complete *un*directed graph with ≥ *Z* nodes, contains a monochromatic complete graph on n nodes.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] In terms of the partition calculus, Ramsey's theorem can be stated as $\aleph _{0}\rightarrow (\aleph _{0})_{k}^{n}$ for all finite *n* and *k*.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Wacław Sierpiński showed that the Ramsey theorem does not extend to graphs of size $\aleph _{1}$ by showing that $2^{\aleph _{0}}\nrightarrow (\aleph _{1})_{2}^{2}$ .
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] In particular, the continuum hypothesis implies that $\aleph _{1}\nrightarrow (\aleph _{1})_{2}^{2}$ .
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Moore has strengthened this result further.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] On the positive side, a Ramsey cardinal is a large cardinal $\kappa$ axiomatically defined to satisfy the related formula: $\kappa \rightarrow (\kappa )_{2}^{<\omega }$ .
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The existence of Ramsey cardinals cannot be proved in ZFC.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] In reverse mathematics, there is a significant difference in proof strength between the versions of Ramsey's theorem.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Some are equally strong as one of the big five subsystems in reverse mathematics, but others are not.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] By a theorem of David Seetapun, the graph version of the theorem is weaker than ACA0, and (combining Seetapun's result with others) it does not fall into one of the big five subsystems.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Let $RT_{k}^{n}$ denote Ramsey's theorem for when we *k*-color the *n*-sized subsets of the natural numbers $\mathbb {N}$ , and let $RT_{<\infty }^{n}:=\forall k,RT_{k}^{n}$ denote Ramsey's theorem for any finite *k* with a single fixed *n*.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] It is a **stable coloring** iff $\forall n\in \mathbb {N}$ , there exists some color i , such that $c(n,m)=i$ for all large enough *m*.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] The **Stable Ramsey's Theorem for Pairs** $SRT_{k}^{2}$ is defined as Ramsey's theorem for when we stably k-color the edges of the complete graph on $\mathbb {N}$ .
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] $\varphi (0)\to \forall n(\varphi (n)\to \varphi (Sn))\to \forall n,\varphi (n)$ for each $\phi$ that is a $\Delta _{2}^{0}$ formula without quantification over set variables.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] From the recursion theory side, the power of $RT_{2}^{n}$ is that it allows us to construct the sets at exactly the level of $\emptyset ^{(n-2)}$ , using the notation for Turing jumps.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-s-theorem] Over ZF, the graph version implies the classical Kőnig's lemma, whereas the converse implication does not hold, since Kőnig's lemma is equivalent to countable choice from finite sets in this setting.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] A typical result in Ramsey theory starts with some mathematical structure that is then cut into pieces.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] How big must the original structure be in order to ensure that at least one of the pieces has a given interesting property?
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] This idea can be defined as partition regularity.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] For example, consider a complete graph of order *n*; that is, there are *n* vertices and each vertex is connected to every other vertex by an edge.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] A complete graph of order 3 is called a triangle.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] Now colour each edge either red or blue.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] How large must *n* be in order to ensure that there is either a blue triangle or a red triangle?
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] See the article on Ramsey's theorem for a rigorous proof.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] Another way to express this result is as follows: at any party with at least six people, there are three people who are all either mutual acquaintances (each one knows the other two) or mutual strangers (none of them knows either of the other two).
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] The special case above has *c* = 2 and *n*1 = *n*2 = 3.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] A theorem similar to van der Waerden's theorem is *Schur's theorem*: for any given *c* there is a number *N* such that if the numbers 1, 2, ..., *N* are coloured with *c* different colours, then there must be a pair of integers *x*, *y* such that *x*, *y*, and *x*+*y* are all the same colour.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] Many generalizations of this theorem exist, including Rado's theorem, Rado–Folkman–Sanders theorem, Hindman's theorem, and the Milliken–Taylor theorem.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] A classic reference for these and many other results in Ramsey theory is Graham, Rothschild, Spencer and Solymosi, updated and expanded in 2015 to its first new edition in 25 years.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] Results in Ramsey theory typically have two primary characteristics.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] Firstly, they are unconstructive: they may show that some structure exists, but they give no process for finding this structure (other than brute-force search).
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] For instance, the pigeonhole principle is of this form.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] Secondly, while Ramsey theory results do say that sufficiently large objects must necessarily contain a given structure, often the proof of these results requires these objects to be enormously large – bounds that grow exponentially, or even as fast as the Ackermann function are not uncommon.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] In some small niche cases, upper and lower bounds are improved, but not in general.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] In many cases these bounds are artifacts of the proof, and it is not known whether they can be substantially improved.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] In other cases it is known that any bound must be extraordinarily large, sometimes even greater than any primitive recursive function; see the Paris–Harrington theorem for an example.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] Graham's number, one of the largest numbers ever used in serious mathematical proof, is an upper bound for a problem related to Ramsey theory.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] Another large example is the Boolean Pythagorean triples problem.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] Theorems in Ramsey theory are generally one of the following two types.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] Many such theorems, which are modeled after Ramsey's theorem itself, assert that in every partition of a large structured object, one of the classes necessarily contains its own structured object, but gives no information about which class this is.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] In other cases, the reason behind a *Ramsey-type* result is that the largest partition class always contains the desired substructure.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] The results of this latter kind are called either *density results* or *Turán-type result*, after Turán's theorem.
[src:ramsey-theory/ramsey-theory] Notable examples include Szemerédi's theorem, which is such a strengthening of van der Waerden's theorem, and the density version of the Hales-Jewett theorem.
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] In discrete mathematics, **Schur's theorem** is any of several theorems of the mathematician Issai Schur.
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] In differential geometry, **Schur's theorem** is a theorem of Axel Schur.
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] In functional analysis, **Schur's theorem** is often called Schur's property, also due to Issai Schur.
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] In Ramsey theory, **Schur's theorem** states that for every positive integer *c*, there exists a positive integer *S*, such that for every partition of the integers $\{1,\ldots ,S\}$ into *c* parts, one of the parts contains integers *x*, *y* and *z* with $x+y=z$ .
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] For every positive integer *c*, *S*(*c*) denotes the smallest number *S* such that for every partition of the integers $\{1,\ldots ,S\}$ into *c* parts, one of the parts contains integers *x*, *y*, and *z* with $x+y=z$ .
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] Schur's theorem ensures that *S*(*c*) is well-defined for every positive integer *c*.
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] The numbers of the form *S*(*c*) are called **Schur's numbers**.
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] Folkman's theorem generalizes Schur's theorem by stating that there exist arbitrarily large sets of integers, all of whose nonempty sums belong to the same part.
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] Using this definition, the only known Schur numbers are *S*(*n*) = 2, 5, 14, 45, and 161 (sequence A030126 in the OEIS).
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] The proof that *S*(5) = 161 was announced in 2017 and required 2 petabytes of space.
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] In combinatorics, **Schur's theorem** tells the number of ways for expressing a given number as a (non-negative, integer) linear combination of a fixed set of relatively prime numbers.
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] As a result, for every set of relatively prime numbers $\{a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n}\}$ there exists a value of x such that every larger number is representable as a linear combination of $\{a_{1},\ldots ,a_{n}\}$ in at least one way.
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] This consequence of the theorem can be recast in a familiar context considering the problem of changing an amount using a set of coins.
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] If the denominations of the coins are relatively prime numbers (such as 2 and 5) then any sufficiently large amount can be changed using only these coins.
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] In differential geometry, **Schur's theorem** compares the distance between the endpoints of a space curve $C^{*}$ to the distance between the endpoints of a corresponding plane curve C of less curvature.
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] Suppose $C(s)$ is a plane curve with curvature $\kappa (s)$ which makes a convex curve when closed by the chord connecting its endpoints, and $C^{*}(s)$ is a curve of the same length with curvature $\kappa ^{*}(s)$ .
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] Let d denote the distance between the endpoints of C and $d^{*}$ denote the distance between the endpoints of $C^{*}$ .
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] Schur's theorem is usually stated for $C^{2}$ curves, but John M.
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] Sullivan has observed that the standard proof applies to curves of finite total curvature (the statement is slightly different).
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] Mohammad Ghomi generalized Schur's theorem to curves in Cartan-Hadamard manifolds.
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] In linear algebra, Schur’s theorem is referred to as either the triangularization of a square matrix with complex entries, or of a square matrix with real entries and real eigenvalues.
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] In functional analysis and the study of Banach spaces, Schur's theorem, due to I.
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] Schur, often refers to Schur's property, that for certain spaces, weak convergence implies convergence in the norm.
[src:ramsey-theory/schur-s-theorem] In number theory, Issai Schur showed in 1912 that for every nonconstant polynomial *p*(*x*) with integer coefficients, if *S* is the set of all nonzero values ${\begin{Bmatrix}p(n)\neq 0:n\in \mathbb {N} \end{Bmatrix}}$ , then the set of primes that divide some member of *S* is infinite.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] In arithmetic combinatorics, **Szemerédi's theorem** is a result concerning arithmetic progressions in subsets of the integers.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] In 1936, Erdős and Turán conjectured that every set of integers *A* with positive natural density contains a *k*-term arithmetic progression for every *k*.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] Endre Szemerédi proved the conjecture in 1975.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] Szemerédi's theorem asserts that a subset of the natural numbers with positive upper density contains an arithmetic progression of length *k* for all positive integers *k*.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] such that every subset of {1, 2, ..., *N*} of size at least $\delta N$ contains an arithmetic progression of length *k*.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] Another formulation uses the function *r**k*(*N*), the size of the largest subset of {1, 2, ..., *N*} without an arithmetic progression of length *k*.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] That is, *r**k*(*N*) grows less than linearly with *N*.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] Van der Waerden's theorem, a precursor of Szemerédi's theorem, was proved in 1927.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] The cases *k* = 1 and *k* = 2 of Szemerédi's theorem are trivial.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] The case *k* = 3, known as Roth's theorem, was established in 1953 by Klaus Roth via an adaptation of the Hardy–Littlewood circle method.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] Szemerédi next proved the case *k* = 4 through combinatorics.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] Using an approach similar to the one he used for the case *k* = 3, Roth gave a second proof for *k* = 4 in 1972.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] The general case was settled in 1975, also by Szemerédi, who developed an ingenious and complicated extension of his previous combinatorial argument for *k* = 4 (called "a masterpiece of combinatorial reasoning" by Erdős).
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] Several other proofs are now known, the most important being those by Hillel Furstenberg in 1977, using ergodic theory, and by Timothy Gowers in 2001, using both Fourier analysis and combinatorics while also introducing what is now called the Gowers norm.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] Terence Tao has called the various proofs of Szemerédi's theorem a "Rosetta stone" for connecting disparate fields of mathematics.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] It is an open problem to determine the exact growth rate of *r**k*(*N*).
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] The lower bound is due to O'Bryant building on the work of Behrend, Rankin, and Elkin.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] For small *k*, there are tighter bounds than the general case.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] When *k* = 3, Bourgain, Heath-Brown, Szemerédi, Sanders, and Bloom established progressively smaller upper bounds, and Bloom and Sisask then proved the first bound that broke the so-called "logarithmic barrier".
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] respectively due to O'Bryant, and Bloom and Sisask (the latter built upon the breakthrough result of Kelley and Meka, who obtained the same upper bound, with "1/9" replaced by "1/12").
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] A multidimensional generalization of Szemerédi's theorem was first proven by Hillel Furstenberg and Yitzhak Katznelson using ergodic theory.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] Timothy Gowers, Vojtěch Rödl and Jozef Skokan with Brendan Nagle, Rödl, and Mathias Schacht, and Terence Tao provided combinatorial proofs.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] Leibman and Bergelson's result also holds in a multidimensional setting.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] The finitary version of Szemerédi's theorem can be generalized to finite additive groups including vector spaces over finite fields.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] The finite field analog can be used as a model for understanding the theorem in the natural numbers.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] The problem of obtaining bounds in the k=3 case of Szemerédi's theorem in the vector space $\mathbb {F} _{3}^{n}$ is known as the cap set problem.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] The Green–Tao theorem asserts the prime numbers contain arbitrarily long arithmetic progressions.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] It is not implied by Szemerédi's theorem because the primes have density 0 in the natural numbers.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] As part of their proof, Ben Green and Tao introduced a "relative" Szemerédi theorem which applies to subsets of the integers (even those with 0 density) satisfying certain pseudorandomness conditions.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] A more general relative Szemerédi theorem has since been given by David Conlon, Jacob Fox, and Yufei Zhao.
[src:ramsey-theory/szemerédi-s-theorem] The Erdős conjecture on arithmetic progressions would imply both Szemerédi's theorem and the Green–Tao theorem.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] This was conjectured by Pierre Joseph Henry Baudet in 1921.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Waerden heard of it in 1926 and published his proof in 1927, titled *Beweis einer Baudetschen Vermutung [Proof of Baudet's conjecture]*.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] For example, when *r* = 2, you have two colors, say red and blue.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] and no three integers of the same color form an arithmetic progression.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] But you can't add a ninth integer to the end without creating such a progression.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] If you add a red 9, then the red 3, 6, and 9 are in arithmetic progression.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Alternatively, if you add a blue 9, then the blue 1, 5, and 9 are in arithmetic progression.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] In fact, there is no way of coloring 1 through 9 without creating such a progression (it can be proved by considering examples).
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] It is an open problem to determine the values of *W*(*r*, *k*) for most values of *r* and *k*.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] The proof of the theorem provides only an upper bound.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] For the case of *r* = 2 and *k* = 3, for example, the argument given below shows that it is sufficient to color the integers {1, ..., 325} with two colors to guarantee there will be a single-colored arithmetic progression of length 3.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] But in fact, the bound of 325 is very loose; the minimum required number of integers is only 9.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Any coloring of the integers {1, ..., 9} will have three evenly spaced integers of one color.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] But actually, you don't need that many integers to guarantee a single-colored progression of length 3; you only need 27.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] An open problem is the attempt to reduce the general upper bound to any 'reasonable' function.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Ronald Graham offered a prize of US$1000 for showing *W*(2, *k*) < 2*k*2.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] In addition, he offered a US$250 prize for a proof of his conjecture involving more general *off-diagonal* van der Waerden numbers, stating *W*(2; 3, *k*) ≤ *k**O(1)*, while mentioning numerical evidence suggests *W*(2; 3, *k*) = *k*2 + *o(1)*.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Ben Green disproved this latter conjecture and proved super-polynomial counterexamples to *W*(2; 3, *k*) < *k*r for any *r*.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] by first establishing a similar result for Szemerédi's theorem, which is a stronger version of Van der Waerden's theorem.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] The previously best-known bound was due to Saharon Shelah and proceeded via first proving a result for the Hales–Jewett theorem, which is another strengthening of Van der Waerden's theorem.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] The best lower bound currently known for $W(2,k)$ is that for all positive $\varepsilon$ we have $W(2,k)>2^{k}/k^{\varepsilon }$ , for all sufficiently large k .
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] The following proof is due to Ron Graham, B.L.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Khinchin gives a fairly simple proof of the theorem without estimating *W*(*r*, *k*).
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] We will prove the special case mentioned above, that *W*(2, 3) ≤ 325.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] We will find three elements of {1, ..., 325} in arithmetic progression that are the same color.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Since each integer is colored either red or blue, each block is colored in one of 32 different ways.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] By the pigeonhole principle, there are two blocks among the first 33 blocks that are colored identically.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Among the three integers 5*b*1 + 1, 5*b*1 + 2, 5*b*1 + 3, there must be at least two that are of the same color.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Suppose (without loss of generality) that these two integers are both red.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] If 5*b*1 + *a*3 is red, then we have found our arithmetic progression: 5*b*1 + *a**i* are all red.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Since *a*3 ≤ 5, 5*b*1 + *a*3 is in the *b*1 block, and since the *b*2 block is colored identically, 5*b*2 + *a*3 is also blue.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Consider the integer 5*b*3 + *a*3, which must be ≤ 325.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] But if it is blue, then 5*b*1 + *a*3, 5*b*2 + *a*3, and 5*b*3 + *a*3 form a blue arithmetic progression.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] One begins by dividing the integers into 2·37·(2·37 + 1) + 1 groups of 7(2·37 + 1) integers each; of the first 37·(2·37 + 1) + 1 groups, two must be colored identically.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Divide each of these two groups into 2·37+1 subgroups of 7 integers each; of the first 37 + 1 subgroups in each group, two of the subgroups must be colored identically.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Within each of these identical subgroups, two of the first four integers must be the same color, say red; this implies either a red progression or an element of a different color, say blue, in the same subgroup.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Since we have two identically-colored subgroups, there is a third subgroup, still in the same group that contains an element which, if either red or blue, would complete a red or blue progression, by a construction analogous to the one for *W*(2, 3).
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] The proof for *W*(2, 3) depends essentially on proving that *W*(32, 2) ≤ 33.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] We divide the integers {1,...,325} into 65 'blocks', each of which can be colored in 32 different ways, and then show that two blocks of the first 33 must be the same color, and there is a block colored the opposite way.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] By a double induction on the number of colors and the length of the progression, the theorem is proved in general.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] where *a* is the basepoint, the *s*'s are positive step-sizes, and the *i*'s range from 0 to *L* − 1.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] A *d*-dimensional AP is *homogeneous* for some coloring when it is all the same color.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] A *D-dimensional arithmetic progression with benefits* is all numbers of the form above, but where you add on some of the "boundary" of the arithmetic progression, i.e. some of the indices *i*'s can be equal to *L*.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] The sides you tack on are ones where the first *k* *i*'s are equal to *L*, and the remaining *i*'s are less than *L*.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] The boundaries of a D-dimensional AP with benefits are these additional arithmetic progressions of dimension $d-1,d-2,d-3,d-4$ , down to 0.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] The 0-dimensional arithmetic progression is the single point at index value $(L,L,L,L,\ldots ,L)$ .
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] A D-dimensional AP with benefits is *homogeneous* when each of the boundaries are individually homogeneous, but different boundaries do not have to necessarily have the same color.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Next define the quantity MinN(*L*, *D*, *N*) to be the least integer so that any assignment of N colors to an interval of length MinN or more necessarily contains a homogeneous D-dimensional arithmetical progression with benefits.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Note that MinN(*L*,1,*N*) is an upper bound for Van der Waerden's number.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] First, if you have an *n*-coloring of the interval 1...*I*, you can define a *block coloring* of *k*-size blocks.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Just consider each sequence of *k* colors in each *k* block to define a unique color.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] *k*-blocking an *n* coloring of length *l* produces an *n**k* coloring of length l/*k*.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] So given a *n*-coloring of an interval *I* of size $M\cdot \operatorname {MinN} (L,1,n^{M}))$ you can *M*-block it into an *n**M* coloring of length $\operatorname {MinN} (L,1,n^{M})$ .
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] This is the definition of a *d* + 1 dimensional arithmetic progression, so you have a homogeneous *d* + 1 dimensional AP.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] The new stride parameter s*D* + 1 is defined to be the distance between the blocks.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] The boundaries you get now are all old boundaries, plus their translations into identically colored blocks, because iD+1 is always less than L.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] The only boundary which is not like this is the 0-dimensional point when $i_{1}=i_{2}=\cdots =i_{D+1}=L$ .
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] This is a single point, and is automatically homogeneous.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Given an n-coloring of an interval of size MinN(*L*,*n*,*n*), by definition, you can find an arithmetic sequence with benefits of dimension n of length L.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] But now, the number of "benefit" boundaries is equal to the number of colors, so one of the homogeneous boundaries, say of dimension k, has to have the same color as another one of the homogeneous benefit boundaries, say the one of dimension *p* < *k*.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] This allows a length *L* + 1 arithmetic sequence (of dimension 1) to be constructed, by going along a line inside the *k*-dimensional boundary which ends right on the *p*-dimensional boundary, and including the terminal point in the *p*-dimensional boundary.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] This constructs a sequence of dimension 1, and the "benefits" are automatic, just add on another point of whatever color.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] To include this boundary point, one has to make the interval longer by the maximum possible value of the stride, which is certainly less than the interval size.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] So doubling the interval size will definitely work, and this is the reason for the factor of two.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Base case: MinN(1,*d*,*n*) = 1, i.e. if you want a length 1 homogeneous d-dimensional arithmetic sequence, with or without benefits, you have nothing to do.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] So this forms the base of the induction.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] The Van der Waerden theorem itself is the assertion that MinN(*L*,1,*N*) is finite, and it follows from the base case and the induction steps.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Furstenberg and Weiss proved an equivalent form of the theorem in 1978, using ergodic theory.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] The proof of the above theorem is delicate, and the reader is referred to.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] With this recurrence theorem, the van der Waerden theorem can be proved in the ergodic-theoretic style.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] Then we can repeat this process to find that there exists at least one partition that contains infinitely many progressions of length ${\textstyle N}$ , for infinitely many ${\textstyle N}$ , and that is the partition we want.
[src:ramsey-theory/van-der-waerden-s-theorem] By the triangle inequality, we then immediately have ${\textstyle d(T^{m+is}z,T^{m+js}z)<{\frac {3}{4}}}$ for ${\textstyle i,j=0,\dots ,N}$ .
